set('profile_title', 'Associate Professor of Finance, Stephen M. Ross School of Business');
set('profile_content', <<<HTML
	<p>Uday Rajan is an Associate Professor of Finance at the Stephen M. Ross School of Business. He obtained a PhD in Economics from Stanford University in 1995 and an MSIA from Carnegie Mellon University in 1986. He was a Vice President in fixed income research at Drexel Burnham Lambert in the late 1980s. He taught at Carnegie Mellon University until 2004, and has been at the Ross School since then. His research focuses on informational frictions such as adverse selection and moral hazard and their effect on market transactions, with recent work on the role of the board in the presence of activist investors and on the default behavior of subprime mortgages in the years before the financial crisis. Current projects include the role of credit rating agencies in the corporate and sovereign debt markets. His research has been published in the <em>American Economic Review</em>, the <em>Journal of Finance</em>, the <em>Journal of Financial Economics</em>, and <em>Management Science</em>. He is an Associate Editor of the <em>Journal of Finance</em> and <em>Management Science</em> and has been an editorial review board member at Marketing Science. He is currently on the board of the Finance Theory Group. He has received MBA teaching awards at the Ross School and at Carnegie Mellon, and a PhD teaching award at the Ross School.</p>
